#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:264
msgid "What can this plugin do and how does it work?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:269
msgid ""
"This plugin is privacy-oriented: optimization runs on your server and "
"does not require sending your site data to third-party services."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:271
msgid ""
"WP Optimizer is modular, so you can enable only the features you need "
"to keep the plugin overhead low."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:273
msgid ""
"Server enhancements such as compression, browser caching, "
"and .htaccess rules."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:274
msgid ""
"Caching layers for queries, database results, objects, and static "
"pages."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:275
msgid "Minification for HTML, CSS, and JavaScript."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:276
msgid "Local image optimization and conversion workflows."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:277
msgid "Database cleanup, optimization, and backups."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:278
msgid "Security hardening and WordPress behavior toggles."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:279
msgid "Update controls, diagnostics, logs, and admin utilities."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:281
msgid ""
"Because modules can affect different parts of WordPress, the safest "
"approach is to enable one feature at a time and test the front end "
"after each change."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:288
msgid "What should I enable first on a live site?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:292
msgid ""
"Start with lower-risk optimizations, then move to the more aggressive "
"ones only after testing."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:294
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Begin with <a href=\"%s\">browser cache and compression settings</a> "
"because they usually improve delivery without changing page logic."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:295
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Configure <a href=\"%s\">media optimization</a> for new uploads before "
"launching large bulk jobs."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:296
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Create a <a href=\"%s\">database backup</a> before cleanup tasks or "
"bigger tuning sessions."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:297
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Add <a href=\"%s\">cache</a> and <a href=\"%s\">minify</a> last, "
"enabling one option at a time and verifying the front end after each "
"step."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:305
msgid "Where can I configure optimization parameters?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:309
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Most optimization options are configurable in the <a "
"href=\"%s\">Modules Options panel</a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:310
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Global tasks such as cron, module activation, telemetry, reset, "
"export, and restore are available from the <a href=\"%s\">Settings "
"page</a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:317
msgid "Can cache or minify break my layout?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:321
msgid ""
"Yes. Aggressive caching and front-end minification can expose "
"conflicts in themes or plugins that rely on specific asset order, "
"inline scripts, or dynamic output."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:323
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Enable <a href=\"%s\">minify</a> gradually: HTML, CSS, and JavaScript "
"do not need to be turned on all at once."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:324
#, php-format
msgid ""
"After each change, clear or reset <a href=\"%s\">cache</a> and test "
"important pages while logged out as well."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:325
msgid ""
"If something breaks, disable the last option you enabled first. That "
"is usually the fastest way to isolate the conflict."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:333
msgid "How does the media optimizer work?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:337
msgid "Media optimizer works in three different ways:"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:339
#, php-format
msgid ""
"By a scheduled event it's able to collect and optimize any media "
"uploaded daily. <a href='%s'>Here</a> you can configure all schedule "
"related settings."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:340
msgid ""
"By a specific path scanner, Media optimizer will run a background "
"activity to optimize all images present in the input path."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:341
msgid ""
"By a whole database scanner, Media optimizer will run a background "
"activity to check all images saved in your WordPress library "
"optimizing each image and every thumbnail associated."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:343
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Any image optimization will be run following your settings set <a "
"href=\"%s\">Here</a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:350
msgid "Why are image optimization jobs not starting?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:354
msgid ""
"Bulk image optimization runs in background, so it depends on the "
"plugin scheduler and on image libraries available on the server."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:356
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Verify that <a href=\"%s\">cron is active</a>; background jobs will "
"not progress if scheduled tasks are not running."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:357
msgid ""
"Check that Imagick or GD is available in PHP. Imagick gives the best "
"coverage, but GD can still handle basic processing."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:358
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Review your <a href=\"%s\">media settings</a> before starting a full-"
"library scan so the job uses the correct quality and format options."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:366
msgid "Do I need Redis or Memcached for object cache?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:370
msgid ""
"Only the object cache feature requires Redis or Memcached. The other "
"optimization modules can still be used without them."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:372
#, php-format
msgid ""
"If your server does not provide Redis or Memcached, leave <a "
"href=\"%s\">object cache</a> disabled."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:373
msgid ""
"Static page cache, database/query cache, browser cache, compression, "
"and minify do not depend on an external object cache server."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:381
msgid "How can I clean the database safely?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:385
msgid ""
"Database cleanup is most useful when you do it conservatively and with "
"a rollback path ready."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:387
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Create a fresh <a href=\"%s\">database backup</a> before deleting "
"revisions, transients, orphaned data, or other leftovers."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:388
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Run cleanup tasks from the <a href=\"%s\">Database module</a> when the "
"site is stable and no import, migration, or major update is running."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:389
msgid ""
"If the result is not what you expected, restore the backup first "
"instead of guessing which rows changed."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:397
msgid "Can I export settings before major changes?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:401
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Yes. The <a href=\"%s\">Settings page</a> lets you export, import, "
"reset, or restore plugin options."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:402
msgid ""
"Use an export before testing aggressive cache, minify, or security "
"changes so you can quickly return to a known-good configuration."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:409
msgid "Does WP Optimizer work on multisite?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:413
msgid "Yes. The plugin supports multisite and can be network-activated."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:414
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Even on multisite, test optimization changes gradually from the <a "
"href=\"%s\">module settings</a> because each subsite may use different "
"themes, plugins, and traffic patterns."
msgstr ""

